  mso-border-themetint:153;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;line-height:
  normal'><span style='font-size:9.0pt'>This requires the ability to execute
  the following code:<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:0in;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:0in;
  margin-left:.5in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;line-height:normal'><span
  style='font-size:9.0pt'>String currentProviders =
  Settings.Secure.getString(Settings.Secure.LOCATION_PROVIDERS_ALLOWED);<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:0in;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:0in;
  margin-left:.5in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;line-height:normal'><span
  style='font-size:9.0pt'>String newProviders =
  currentProviders.add(&quot;GPS&quot;);<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:0in;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:0in;
  margin-left:.5in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;line-height:normal'><span
  style='font-size:9.0pt'>boolean Settings.Secure.putInt(LOCATION_PROVIDERS_ALLOWED,newProviders);<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;line-height:
  normal'><span style='font-size:9.0pt'>The above code requires
  WRITE_SECURE_SETTINGS permission, which  is NOT granted to a Device Owner
  application, except through use of the DevicePolicyManager.setSecureSetting()
  API, which limits the set of values that can be passed, with
  “LOCATION_PROVIDERS_ALLOWED” NOT being included.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;line-height:
  normal'><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-size:9.0pt;
  color:red'>The WirelessMgr CSP does provide a way to do this, but it is
  currently NOT exposed by OemConfig, hence no DIRECT method is currently
  planned to be available for a Device Owner EMM to be able to control this.<span
  style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>Nonetheless, it could be accomplished
  INDIRECTLY, via OemConfig, by submitting XML via the devadminStep</span></b><b
  style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-size:9.0pt'><o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  </td>

  <p class=MsoNormal style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;line-height:

 <tr style='mso-yfti-irow:20;page-break-inside:avoid'>

  accent1;mso-border-themetint:153;border-top:none;mso-border-top-alt:solid #8EAADB .5pt;

  background:#D9E2F3;mso-background-themecolor:accent1;mso-background-themetint:
  51;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt'>
  <p class=MsoListParagraph style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
  mso-add-space:auto;text-indent:-.25in;line-height:normal;mso-list:l0 level1 lfo8;
  mso-yfti-cnfc:68'><![if !supportLists]><b><span style='font-size:9.0pt;
  mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-latin'><span
  style='mso-list:Ignore'>21.<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
  </span></span></span></b><![endif]><b><span style='font-size:9.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width=624 style='width:6.5in;border-top:none;border-left:none;border-bottom:
  solid #8EAADB 1.0pt;mso-border-bottom-themecolor:accent1;mso-border-bottom-themetint:
  153;border-right:solid #8EAADB 1.0pt;mso-border-right-themecolor:accent1;
  mso-border-right-themetint:153;mso-border-top-alt:solid #8EAADB .5pt;
  mso-border-top-themecolor:accent1;mso-border-top-themetint:153;mso-border-left-alt:
  solid #8EAADB .5pt;mso-border-left-themecolor:accent1;mso-border-left-themetint:
  153;mso-border-alt:solid #8EAADB .5pt;mso-border-themecolor:accent1;
  mso-border-themetint:153;background:#D9E2F3;mso-background-themecolor:accent1;
  mso-background-themetint:51;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;line-height:
  normal;mso-yfti-cnfc:64'><span style='font-size:9.0pt'>The PersistMgr CSP
  provides functions to manage the persistence of XML applied via MX and
  automatically reapply it following an Enterprise Reset.<span
  style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>Such functions are not intended for use
  except by MX-centric applications and hence are not currently planned to be
  exposed via OemConfig.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>When Staging an
  EMM Agent using StageNow, the PersistMgr CSP can still be used to persist the
  XML necessary to re-install and re-enroll the EMM Agent following an
  Enterprise Reset.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>If the EMM has
  actions that it wants to be persistent, it should store them persistently
  itself and re-apply them once it is re-enrolled again following the
  Enterprise Reset rather than try and rely on the PersistMgr CSP to re-apply
  them.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>Since the EMM Agent may need to
  re-apply other things besides those set (directly or indirectly) via MX, it
  makes sense to treat all actions or configurations the EMM Agent wants to
  persist the same, regardless of whether they are ultimately accomplished
  using MX, OemConfig, AEDO APIs, etc.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;line-height:
  normal;mso-yfti-cnfc:64'><span style='font-size:9.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;line-height:
  normal;mso-yfti-cnfc:64'><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
  style='font-size:9.0pt;color:red'>Recent discussions <!-- with AirWatch--> have led
  to a set of use cases where the EMM Agent is not StageNow, but instead is
  Staged using one or more Google methods (e.g. NFC Bump, QR Code, Hash Tag,
  Google Account, or Zero Touch).<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>In
  such cases, we cannot count on StageNow to handle persistence of the EMM
  Agent.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>The ask is for the EMM Agent to
  have a way to request (directly or as a result of a common sent from the
  server) that the steps required to re-install, re-enroll, and re-configure it
  following an Enterprise Reset be made persistent.<span
  style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>This would require some way to interact
  with PersistMgr, preferably via OemConfig so it does not require using any
  Zebra-specific APIs.<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  <p class=MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:
  .0001pt;mso-add-space:auto;text-indent:-.25in;line-height:normal;mso-list:
  l6 level1 lfo14;mso-yfti-cnfc:64'><![if !supportLists]><span
  style='font-size:9.0pt;font-family:Symbol;mso-fareast-font-family:Symbol;
  mso-bidi-font-family:Symbol'><span style='mso-list:Ignore'>·<span
  style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
  </span></span></span><![endif]><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
  style='font-size:9.0pt;color:red'>One approach would be to have the EMM
  submit XML INDIRECTLY, via OemConfig, by submitting XML (which uses
  PersistMgr and other CSPs) via the devadminStep.<span
  style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>This would work because PersistMgr will
  still be present in devices and will be available for use by OemConfig even
  if/when EMMs are prohibited from submitting XML directly to MX (e.g.
  beginning in Android Oreo).<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>This would
  require the EMM to continue to use XML, which may be undesirable, but may be
  acceptable since the XML would generally be “canned” and could be sent from
  the Server to the Agent, allowing the Agent to avoid any Zebra-specific
  logic.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>This approach requires no new
  development by Zebra.</span></b><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
  style='font-size:9.0pt'><o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  <p class=MsoListParagraphCxSpLast style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:
  .0001pt;mso-add-space:auto;text-indent:-.25in;line-height:normal;mso-list:
  l6 level1 lfo14;mso-yfti-cnfc:64'><![if !supportLists]><span
  style='font-size:9.0pt;font-family:Symbol;mso-fareast-font-family:Symbol;
  mso-bidi-font-family:Symbol'><span style='mso-list:Ignore'>·<span
  style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
  </span></span></span><![endif]><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
  style='font-size:9.0pt;color:red'>Another approach would be to add a set of
  Managed Configurations to OemConfig to enable persistence of a DO EMM
  Agent.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>There are really only three
  actions likely to be required to persist a DO EMM Agent: Re-install the APK
  (which must be already stored in a persistent location), Re-enroll the APK as
  a DO after it is installed, and send the standard intent to provide the DO
  with enrollment information.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>This
  could all be done using just three new Managed Configurations, which could
  all be of the “hidden write” type to allow the EMM Server to fill them in
  without involving the Device Administrator.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'> 
  </span>A key advantage of this approach is that it eliminates the need for
  the EMM to continue to support MX XML, which is more consistent with our
  overall forward-looking strategy.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>This
  approach requires a small amount of new development work by Zebra to add new
  Managed Configurations.</span></b><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
  style='font-size:9.0pt'><o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
